<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=397#M397">179</a> of 829
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1193 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Brenlo,</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Here is my 2cp regarding the Enchanter Charm issue.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I have played an Enchanter since Beta, its my chosen class.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>My suggestion is a follows. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1. Re-write Charm spell to strip (overwrite) all beneficial buffs on a target when successfully landing;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This solves the overpowering of charmed mobs by buffing the heck out of them after charming and letting them plow through mobs. This prevents pre-buffing a mob while mezzed, rooted,snared etc.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2. While the Charm spell is in effect, the mob is immune to all beneficial spells except heals. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This addresses the overpowering issue with buffing a charmed mob.</DIV>
<DIV>Even making the mob immune to heals as well means it becomes a shorter lived asset, having to charm a mob to kill a mob scenario means the Charm caster must tip the balance in his favor by use of spells or melee, the overall downtime would address the overpowered soloist and risk vs reward concerns. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3.&nbsp;Detrimental spells will still effect the mob.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This allows the mob to be properly attacked/slowed/debuffed by its attacker(s)</DIV>
<DIV>If you/your group needs to slow it in any way to allow you to charm it..&nbsp; it stays slowed to your detriment.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>4. Remove the DPS nerf on charmed mobs.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Having the mob at its base table stats gives it a "natural" lowered ability/DPS over its opponents to the Charm caster/group detriment.</DIV>
<DIV>Having the charmed mob at its base table stats without the ability of buffing addresses the overpowering issue, as well as change in DPS when charm breaks requiring the use of two separate mob tables.</DIV>
<DIV>Even at its base table stats, most/all mobs are a&nbsp;serious threat to Enchanters especially now the Enchanter is without a pet protector. and in a group would require a re-focus of the group efforts to keep the Enchanter alive while re-charm is being cast. or self rune etc.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This also addresses the Risk Vs Reward&nbsp;for a soloist as he/she must address an angry mob, or more if charm breaks early.</DIV>
<DIV>This also addresses the Risk Vs Reward for a&nbsp;group&nbsp;as they address the broken charmed pet problem before the enchanter is&nbsp;killed while still addressing the present mobs in camp. (the more your group slows,dots or otherwise offtanks the mobs means its less useful when re-charmed, detrimental spell effects remain after charming)</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Re-working this single line of spells instead of entire expansion mob tables&nbsp; would be quicker for the Dev team to impliment and test.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I hope you see the merit&nbsp;and logic in this proposal.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Cheers</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Aurbo Skyfyre</DIV>
<DIV>70th season &nbsp;Enchantress</DIV>
<DIV>Kane Bayle&nbsp;</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
