<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/paladin.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=164#M164">184</a> of 829
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1193 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<br>I always thought that SOE was haha-only-serious when the story line for EQ2 was that the mortals became to powerful for their own good, this whole thread proves it.<br>

<br>Part of the problem is that so many of the basic concepts in the game at lower levels don't scale well at upper levels.  We need to come up some new ideas to give to the devs to replace some of these above about 60.<br>

<br>Stun for instance.  We Pallys love our stun, it something that is "ours" for most part.  However, honest and thoughtful paladins will realize that at uber high levels stun has the potential to be unbalancing. The main problem being that stun brings the mob to a complete stop, no casting, no damage, no movement.  Risk is removed for a period of time.<br>

<br>I've been trying to come up with some kind of "partial stun" or "distract" idea.  We could use it to get agro but it wouldn't bring the mob to a complete halt.  The effect might be like a mini-slow plus (mini-dps reduction or mini-ac reduction).  I'm not really sure what it is and what all the implications are as I haven't thought it through all the way.  Basically, something that reduces but does not eliminate risk.<br>

<br>This goes for other classes as well.  Any effect that <i>completly</i> removes risk or damage even for a very short time is going to eventually be nerfed.  It doesn't give the devs enough room to balance gameplay.  We all need to come up with ways for the devs to balance things behind the scenes.  Let the devs tweak small things otherwise they're forced to change big things and then everything goes to hell.<br>

<br>Each class has something thats bugging them.  Each class feels like the devs have forgot about them.  Lets try to come up with some <i>new</i> ideas beyond just "I want what they have".<br>

<br>And now for some more soap boxing :-)<br>

<br><blockquote><hr>BlackNyte wrote:<br><DIV>What about the Paladins below 60?  The levels between 45 and 60 are the slowest most horrible levels for a paladin.</DIV><br><hr></blockquote><br>

<br>I like to second this, as a 53 Paladin who has come back to the game after a long hiatus.  But of course, this is just my current itch...<br>

<br>Basically the impression I'm getting is that all the action is above 65.  I'm having trouble getting there however because it also feels like there aren't many new players anymore filling the high mid-levels.  I'm also having a hard time finding groups that want to play anything other than instanced missions.  Its tough to find anyone willing to help with any quest or roleplaying content anymore.<br>

<br>I started playing EQ just after the Velious expansion came out.  It seems to me that back then everyone had pretty defined roles and things worked pretty well.  Things seem to have become unglued around the time Planes of Power came out.  Many of the classes seemed to lose distinction and I felt like the game in general began to lose focus.  Once we stoped needing each other so much we all got greedy.  I think the devs are trying to get things back into balance now.  Its going to be tough, too many genies have been let out of too many bottles.<br>

<br>I think this is part of what may be bothering the Druids.  The game has become <i>so</i> group and raid-centric that if you solo at all you fall behind and aren't able to catch back up to rejoin the "real" game.  Druids have always felt to me like their big "pro" was soloing and so naturally they would tend to be "also" in groups.  This didn't used to be such a big problem but now I think its become crippling.  Groups feel they have to be so efficent that they can't let in any "also" players.  And thats sad.<br>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
